  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Cambridge Bible for Schools and Colleges",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "bld",
        "text": "14",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "ordained twelve",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "] Hitherto they had been His friends and disciples in a wider sense, now He formally called them, and joined them in a united band, that (i) they “might be with Him” (comp. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Acts 1:21",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "), (ii) that He might “send them forth” as heralds to preach, and (iii) that they “might have power to cast out demons,” for the words “",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "to heal sicknesses",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "” are omitted in some of the best MSS.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "(i) ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "The number of the Apostles",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". The number selected, answering to the twelve sons of Jacob, was small indeed as compared with the hundreds who enrolled themselves as disciples of a Hillel or a Gamaliel, and their position in life was humble and obscure, but “",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "the weak things of the world were to confound the things which are mighty",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "” (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Corinthians 1:27",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "), and these Twelve were to be the Twelve Pillars of the Church.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "(ii) ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "Their calling and training",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". Observe that the calling and training of the Twelve was a most important part of our Lord’s ministerial work. (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "a",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ") Immediately after His Baptism and Temptation He began to prepare some of them for their future vocation (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "John 1:35-51",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "); (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "b",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ") to their training He devoted the greater part of His time and strength; (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "c",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ") after His resurrection He continued for forty days His personal efforts for their improvement, and (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "d",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ") at last He bestowed upon them His promised gift of the Holy Ghost.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "(iii) ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "Their title",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". The name also which He gave to them deserves attention. He named them ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "Apostles",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Luke 6:13",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "). The word thus rendered means (i) as an adjective, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "despatched",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " or ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "sent forth",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", (ii) as a substantive, the ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "actual delegate",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " of the person who sends him.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "(",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "a",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ") In Classical Greek the word was almost entirely restricted to the meaning of a “naval expedition,” a “fleet despatched on foreign service,” and this meaning entirely superseded any other.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "(",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "b",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ") In the Septuagint the word occurs only once, namely, in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Kings 14:6",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", in the sense of “a messenger,” “one who has a commission from God,” where Abijah says to the wife of Jeroboam, “I am a ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "messenger",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " unto thee of heavy tidings.”",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "(",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "c",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ") With the later Jews the word was in common use, and was the title of those, who were sent from the mother city on any foreign mission, especially the collection of the tribute for the Temple service.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "(",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "d",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ") Thus when He employed it to designate His immediate and most favoured disciples, “our Lord was not introducing a new term, but adopting one which from its current usage would suggest to His hearers the idea of a highly responsible mission.” In ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Hebrews 3:1",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " He Himself is styled “The ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "Apostle",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " and high priest of our profession,” with which compare ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "John 17:18",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". Canon Lightfoot on the ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "Epistle to the Galatians",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", p. 94.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Bengel's Gnomen",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Mark 3:14",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "Δώδεκα",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "twelve",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ") The characteristic notes of an apostle were, an immediate and direct call, a continuous intercourse with Christ, the being an eye-witness, the right of preaching universally [and not merely restricted to one locality], the gift of miracles.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Pulpit Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_sub_title",
        "text": "Verses 14, 15.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " - Out of those who thus came to him, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "he ordained twelve",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " literally, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "he made or appointed twelve.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " They were not solemnly ordained or consecrated to their office until after his resurrection. Their actual consecration (of all of them at least but one, namely, Judas Iscariot) took place when he breathed on them and said, \"Receive ye the Holy Ghost\" (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "John 20:22",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "). But from this time they were his apostles \"designate.\" They were henceforth to Be with him as his attendants and disciples. They were to go forth and preach under his direction, and by his power they were to cast out devils. Several manuscripts add here that they were \"to heal sicknesses,\" but the words are emitted in some of the oldest authorities. The authority over unclean spirits is more formally conveyed later on (see ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Mark 6:7",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "), so that here St. Mark speaks by anticipation. But this shows how much importance was attached to this part of their mission; for it recognizes the spiritual world, and the special purpose of the manifestation of the Son of God, namely, that he might \"destroy the works of the devil.\" ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "He appointed twelve.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " The number twelve symbolizes perfection and universality. The number three indicates what is Divine; and the number four, created things. Three multiplied by four gives twelve, the number of those who were to go forth as apostles into the four quarters of the world - called to the faith of the holy Trinity. Mark 3:14",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Vincent's Word Studies",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "Ordained (ἐποίησεν)",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "Lit., made. Rev., appointed.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "Might send them forth (ἀποστέλλῃ)",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "As apostles. Compare the kindred noun ἀπόστολοι, apostles. ",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  }
]